### Describe the bug

Blazor WebAssembly: When repeated reloads that replace large collections cause the Mono/Blazor WASM linear memory (the Module HEAP ArrayBuffer) to grow and remain at the high-water size. Forcing .NET GC reclaims managed objects but does not shrink the WASM ArrayBuffer. I have a small sample app showing the issue (local workspace).


```
@page "/counter"

<button @onclick="@ReloadData">reload</button>

<div>
    <Virtualize Items="DataSource" Context="appointment">
        <div class="appointment-template" @key="appointment.Id">
            <div class="appointment-subject-container">
                <span class="appointment-span">
                    @appointment.Subject
                </span>
            </div>
            <div class="simple-tooltip">
                ich mag coden
            </div>
        </div>
    </Virtualize>
</div>

@code {
    List<AppointmentData> DataSource = new();
    protected override void OnInitialized()
    {
        DataSource = GenerateAppointments(800);
    }

    public static DateTime GetMonday(DateTime date)
    {
        int diff = (int)date.DayOfWeek - (int)DayOfWeek.Monday;
        if (diff < 0) diff += 7;
        return date.Date.AddDays(-diff);
    }

    private List<AppointmentData> GenerateAppointments(int count)
    {
        var list = new List<AppointmentData>(capacity: count);
        var rand = new Random(); // change from new Random(42) to vary each run
        DateTime baseDate = GetMonday(DateTime.Today.Date);
        var durations = new[] { 30, 45, 60, 90, 120 }; // minutes

        for (int i = 1; i <= count; i++)
        {
            int dayOffset = rand.Next(0, 7);
            int hour = rand.Next(8, 18);
            int minute = rand.Next(0, 2) * 30;
            var start = baseDate.AddDays(dayOffset).AddHours(hour).AddMinutes(minute);
            var end = start.AddMinutes(durations[rand.Next(durations.Length)]);

            int ownerId = ((i - 1) % 3) + 1;
            int roomId = ((i - 1) % 2) + 1;

            list.Add(new AppointmentData
            {
                Id = i,
                Subject = $"Meeting #{i}",
                Location = $"Room {roomId}",
                StartTime = start,
                EndTime = end,
                Description = $"Auto-generated appointment {i}",
                OwnerId = ownerId,
                RoomId = roomId
            });
        }
        return list;
    }

    public class AppointmentData
    {
        public int Id { get; set; }
        public string Subject { get; set; }
        public string Location { get; set; }
        public DateTime StartTime { get; set; }
        public DateTime EndTime { get; set; }
        public string Description { get; set; }
        public bool IsAllDay { get; set; }
        public string RecurrenceRule { get; set; }
        public string RecurrenceException { get; set; }
        public int? RecurrenceID { get; set; }
        public int OwnerId { get; set; }
        public int RoomId { get; set; }
        // public string Icon { get; set; } = LargeIcon.Icon;
    }

    private async Task ReloadData()
    {
        // Replace the list reference instead of clearing and adding to the same list.
        // This helps the renderer and GC avoid retaining references to old items.
        DataSource = GenerateAppointments(800);
        GC.Collect(); GC.WaitForPendingFinalizers(); GC.Collect();
        await Task.Delay(100);
        await InvokeAsync(StateHasChanged);
    }
}
```

### Expected Behavior

**Observed behavior (actual)**

- Repeated reloads cause a large `system / JSArrayBufferData` (example ~100 MB) to appear in heap snapshots.
- Retainer path shows the buffer is held by `Module` / `HEAP`* typed-array views (Mono runtime).
- Calling `GC.Collect()` (and waiting) reclaims managed objects but does not shrink the WASM ArrayBuffer retained by the runtime.
- Attempts to reduce renderer allocations (add `@key`) reduce allocation pressure but do not reclaim the ArrayBuffer once grown.
- None of those fixes shrank the WASM ArrayBuffer once it grew; some reduced allocation pressure but the ArrayBuffer remained sized at the high-water mark. This suggests that the runtime expanded WASM linear memory in response to allocation pressure and does not shrink it automatically.

**Expected behavior**

- Either the runtime should avoid unnecessary WASM heap expansions for normal UI reload patterns, or provide a supported way to reduce/reclaim linear memory when safe. At minimum guidance / mitigations from the runtime team for apps that must frequently replace large collections would be helpful.
- Whether Blazor/Mono should/does shrink the WebAssembly ArrayBuffer under any circumstances; if not, whether we can improve memory usage to avoid repeated expansions in usual scenarios.
- Whether there are specific allocations in the renderer or runtime that cause excessive native heap growth that should be optimized.
- Recommended patterns for Blazor WASM apps that frequently replace large collections to avoid WASM heap growth.
- If this is a bug/regression in the current runtime (Mono/wasm) or a limitation of wasm heap management, and whether there are plans to expose shrink/compaction or reduce expansion triggers.

### Steps To Reproduce


- Build & run the sample Blazor WASM app (project root) with the provided code.
- Example: from project folder: `dotnet run` and open the app in a browser.
- Open DevTools → Memory.
- Use "Allocation instrumentation on timeline" (or Heap snapshot with "Record allocation stacks").
- On the Home page click the `reload` operations repeatedly (these reassign DataSource with many items — e.g., 500–1000 items).
- Stop recording / take heap snapshots and compare before/after.
- Observe the WASM/JS ArrayBuffer growth and retained size in the snapshot (see details below).

