### Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe the problem.

When searching for similar Issues I found one that almost completely matches my question but remained unanswered [#58871](https://github.com/dotnet/aspnetcore/issues/58871)

The issue arises from `@refs` values that may not be yet available when the method runs. One could of course store the related `Task` or try to otherwise defer the work to the next `OnAfterRenderAsync()` iteration. However, this tends to reduce readability and introduces additional complexity into otherwise straightforward logic.

Internally we currently use the following solution:

```
private TaskCompletionSource _nextRenderedFrame = new();

protected override async Task OnAfterRenderAsync(bool firstRender)
{
    _nextRenderedFrame.SetResult();
    _nextRenderedFrame = new();
}

private async Task SomethingThatRequiredFocus() 
{ 
    // ... Something that changes the current state
    StateHasChanged();

    await _nextRenderedFrame.Task; 
    await _myRef.FocusAsync(); // Example of logic that depends on a @ref
}
```



### Describe the solution you'd like

I’d like guidance on whether the `TaskCompletionSource` + `OnAfterRender{Async}` pattern (awaiting the next render before using `@ref`-dependent logic) is considered bad practice in Blazor. If it’s acceptable: is there a more “native”/official .NET or Blazor API or recommended pattern to accomplish the same thing (i.e., await a completed render) without using a custom awaiter?

